26-0015-7|ref=harv}}\n*{{cite book|first=Scott|last=Witmer|title=History of Rock Bands|year=2010|publisher=ABDO|isbn=978-1-60453-692-8|ref=harv|url-access=registration|url=https://archive.org/details/historyofrockban0000witm}}\n*{{cite book|first1=Jeff|last1=Yang|authorlink1=Jeff Yang|first2=Dina|last2=Gan|first3=Terry|last3=Hong|title=Eastern Standard Time: A Guide to Asian Influence on American Culture from Astro Boy to Zen Buddhism|year=1997|publisher=[[Houghton Mifflin Harcourt|Houghton Mifflin]]|isbn=0-395-76341-X|ref=harv|url=https://archive.org/details/easternstandardt00yang}}\n{{div col end}}\n\n[[Category:Glam metal musicians| ]]\n[[Category:Lists of heavy metal bands|Glam metal]]\n", "name_user": "Category adder", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eS:Added the correct date to my source", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/List_of_glam_metal_bands_and_artists"}
{"title_page": "HMS Weymouth (1795)", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2012}}\n{{otherships|HMS Weymouth}}\n{|{{Infobox ship begin}}\n{{Infobox ship image\n|Ship image=\n|Ship caption=\n}}\n{{Infobox ship career\n|Hide header=\n|Ship country=United Kingdom\n|Ship flag={{shipboxflag|UK|naval}}\n|Ship name=''Earl of Mansfield''\n|Ship ordered=\n|Ship builder=Wells & Co. [[Rotherhithe]]\n|Ship laid down=\n|Ship launched=30 September 1795\n|Ship acquired=By purchase on the stocks\n|Ship completed=\n|Ship commissioned=\n|Ship decommissioned=\n|Ship reclassified=\n|Ship in service=\n|Ship out of service=\n|Ship renamed=HMS ''Weymouth''\n|Ship struck=\n|Ship reinstated=\n|Ship honours=\n|Ship captured=\n|Ship fate=Wrecked 21 January 1800\n|Ship status=\n|Ship notes=\n}}\n{{Infobox ship characteristics\n|Hide header=\n|Header caption=<ref name=Winfield>Winfield (2008), p.113.</ref>\n|Ship class=[[Fourth rate]] \n|Ship tons burthen=1416,<ref>Hackman (2001), p.99.</ref> or 1433{{small|{{frac|56|94}}}} ([[Builder's Old Measurement|bm]])\n|Ship length=*{{convert|175|ft|6|in|m|1|abbr=on}} (overall)\n*{{convert|144|ft|1|in|m|1|abbr=on}} (keel)\n|Ship beam={{convert|43|ft|3|in|m|1|abbr=on}}\n|Ship draught=\n|Ship hold depth={{convert|19|ft|7|in|m|1|abbr=on}}\n|Ship sail plan=[[Full rigged ship]]\n|Ship propulsion=Sails\n|Ship complement=344 (Fourth rate)\n|Ship armament=*Fourth rate:\n**Lower deck (LD):28 \u00d7 18-pounder guns\n**Upper [[deck (ship)#Common names|deck]] (UD): 28 x 32-pounder [[carronades]]\n*Transport: 26 guns\n\n|Ship notes=\n}}\n|}\n\n'''HMS ''Weymouth''''' was [[Keel-laying|laid down]] as the [[East Indiaman]] ''Earl of Mansfield''. The British [[Royal Navy]] purchased her on the stocks to use as a 56-gun [[fourth rate]]. She was launched in 1795 but never was [[Ship commissioning|commissioned]] in the Royal Navy. She was transferred in February 1796 to the [[Transport Board (Royal Navy)|Transportation Board]] as a [[Transport (ship)|transport]]. [[Lieutenant (navy)|Lieutenant]] Robert Passmore took command in June 1796. [[Commander (Royal Navy)|Commander]] Charles Ryder succeeded Passmore in July 1798, and Commander Ambrose Crofton replaced Ryder in August 1799.\n\nHaving sailed from [[Portsmouth]], she was wrecked on 21 January 1800 on the [[Shoal|bar]] in the [[Tagus]] on the coast of [[Portugal]] as Crofton was attempting to sail her into [[Lisbon]] harbour.<ref>Hepper (1997), p.94.</ref> Her crew was saved.<ref>[https://hdl.handle.net/2027/mdp.39015036615428?urlappend=%3Bseq=249 ''[[Lloyd's List]]'' \u21164027.]</ref>\n\n==Citations and references==\n'''Citations'''\n{{reflist|30em}}\n'''References'''\n*{{cite book |last=Hackman |first=Rowan |year=2001 |title=Ships of the East India Company |location=Gravesend, Kent |publisher=World Ship Society |isbn=0-905617-96-7 |ref=harv}}\n* Hepper, David J. (1994) ''British Warship Losses in the Age of Sail, 1650-1859''. (Rotherfield: Jean Boudriot). {{ISBN|0-948864-30-3}}\n*{{cite book |first=Rif|last=Winfield|title=British Warships in the Age of Sail 1793\u20131817: Design, Construction, Careers and Fates|publisher=Seaforth|year=2008|isbn=978-1-86176-246-7}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Weymouth (1795)}}\n[[Category:1795 ships]]\n[[Category:Ships built in Rotherhithe]]\n[[Category:Ships of the Royal Navy]]\n[[Category:Maritime incidents in 1800]]\n[[Category:Shipwrecks of Portugal]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2012}}\n{{otherships|HMS Weymouth}}\n{|{{Infobox ship begin}}\n{{Infobox ship image\n|Ship image=\n|Ship caption=\n}}\n{{Infobox ship career\n|Hide header=\n|Ship country=United Kingdom\n|Ship flag={{shipboxflag|UK|naval}}\n|Ship name=''Earl of Mansfield''\n|Ship ordered=\n|Ship builder=Wells & Co. [[Rotherhithe]]\n|Ship laid down=\n|Ship launched=30 September 1795\n|Ship acquired=By purchase on the stocks\n|Ship completed=\n|Ship commissioned=\n|Ship decommissioned=\n|Ship reclassified=\n|Ship in service=\n|Ship out of service=\n|Ship renamed=HMS ''Weymouth''\n|Ship struck=\n|Ship reinstated=\n|Ship honours=\n|Ship captured=\n|Ship fate=Wrecked 21 January 1800\n|Ship status=\n|Ship notes=\n}}\n{{Infobox ship characteristics\n|Hide header=\n|Header caption=<ref name=Winfield>Winfield (2008), p.113.</ref>\n|Ship class=[[Fourth rate]] \n|Ship tons burthen=1416,<ref>Hackman (2001), p.99.</ref> or 1433{{small|{{frac|56|94}}}} ([[Builder's Old Measurement|bm]])\n|Ship length=*{{convert|175|ft|6|in|m|1|abbr=on}} (overall)\n*{{convert|144|ft|1|in|m|1|abbr=on}} (keel)\n|Ship beam={{convert|43|ft|3|in|m|1|abbr=on}}\n|Ship draught=\n|Ship hold depth={{convert|19|ft|7|in|m|1|abbr=on}}\n|Ship sail plan=[[Full rigged ship]]\n|Ship propulsion=Sails\n|Ship complement=344 (Fourth rate)\n|Ship armament=*Fourth rate:\n**Lower deck (LD):28 \u00d7 18-pounder guns\n**Upper [[deck (ship)#Common names|deck]] (UD): 28 x 32-pounder [[carronades]]\n*Transport: 26 guns\n\n|Ship notes=\n}}\n|}\n\n'''HMS ''Weymouth''''' was [[Kell-laying|laid down]] as the [[East Indiaman]] ''Earl of Mansfield''. The British [[Royal Navy]] purchased her on the stocks to use as a 56-gun [[fourth rate]]. She was launched in 1795 but never was [[Ship commissioning|commissioned]] in the Royal Navy. She was transferred in February 1796 to the [[Transport Board (Royal Navy)|Transportation Board]] as a [[Transport (ship)|transport]]. [[Lieutenant (navy)|Lieutenant]] Robert Passmore took command in June 1796. [[Commander (Royal Navy)|Commander]] Charles Ryder succeeded Passmore in July 1798, and Commander Ambrose Crofton replaced Ryder in August 1799.\n\nHaving sailed from [[Portsmouth]], she was wrecked on 21 January 1800 on the [[Shoal|bar]] in the [[Tagus]] on the coast of [[Portugal]] as Crofton was attempting to sail her into [[Lisbon]] harbour.<ref>Hepper (1997), p.94.</ref> Her crew was saved.<ref>[https://hdl.handle.net/2027/mdp.39015036615428?urlappend=%3Bseq=249 ''[[Lloyd's List]]'' \u21164027.]</ref>\n\n==Citations and references==\n'''Citations'''\n{{reflist|30em}}\n'''References'''\n*{{cite book |last=Hackman |first=Rowan |year=2001 |title=Ships of the East India Company |location=Gravesend, Kent |publisher=World Ship Society |isbn=0-905617-96-7 |ref=harv}}\n* Hepper, David J. (1994) ''British Warship Losses in the Age of Sail, 1650-1859''. (Rotherfield: Jean Boudriot). {{ISBN|0-948864-30-3}}\n*{{cite book |first=Rif|last=Winfield|title=British Warships in the Age of Sail 1793\u20131817: Design, Construction, Careers and Fates|publisher=Seaforth|year=2008|isbn=978-1-86176-246-7}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Weymouth (1795)}}\n[[Category:1795 ships]]\n[[Category:Ships built in Rotherhithe]]\n[[Category:Ships of the Royal Navy]]\n[[Category:Maritime incidents in 1800]]\n[[Category:Shipwrecks of Portugal]]\n", "name_user": "Mdnavman", "label": "safe", "comment": "Typo.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/HMS_Weymouth_(1795)"}
{"title_page": "Xavi", "text_new": "{{short description|Spanish association football player and manager}}\n{{Redirect|Xavier Hern\u00e1ndez|the former Major League Baseball player|Xavier Hernandez (baseball)|other uses|Xavi (given name)}}\n{{Spanish name|[[Hern\u00e1ndez]]|Creus}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2020}}\n{{Infobox football biography\n| name = Xavi\n| image = Xavi Hernandez (31521652051).jpg\n| image_size = \n| caption = Xavi in 2016\n| fullname = Xavier Hern\u00e1ndez Creus<ref name=fifalist>{{cite web|title=FIFA World Cup South Africa 2010: List of Players|url=https://www.fifa.com/mm/document/tournament/competition/01/22/85/78/fwc_2010_squadlists.pdf|publisher=F\u00e9d\u00e9ration Internationale de Football Association (FIFA)|accessdate=13 September 2013|page=29|format=PDF|date=4 June 2010}}</ref>\n| birth_date = {{Birth date and age|1980|1|25|df=y}}<ref name=fifalist/>\n| birth_place = [[Terrassa]], Spain\n| height = 1.70 m<ref>{{cite web |title=\"Xavi profile\" |url=http://al-saddclub.com/the-players/xavi-hernandez |website=al-saddclub.com |language=en}}</ref>\n| position = [[Midfielder]]\n| currentclub = [[Al Sadd SC|Al Sadd]] (manager)\n| youthyears1 = 1991\u20131997\n| youthclubs1 = [[FC Barcelona|Barcelona]]\n| years1 = 1997\u20131999\n| clubs1 = [[FC Barcelona B|Barcelona B]]\n| caps1 = 55\n| goals1 = 3\n| years2 = 1998\u20132015\n| clubs2 = [[FC Barcelona|Barcelona]]\n| caps2 = 505\n| goals2 = 58\n| years3 = 2015\u20132019\n| clubs3 = [[Al Sadd SC|Al Sadd]]\n| caps3 = 82\n| goals3 = 21\n| totalcaps = 642\n| totalgoals = 82\n| nationalyears1 = 1997\n| nationalteam1 = [[Spain national under-17 football team|Spain U17]]\n| nationalcaps1 = 10\n| nationalgoals1 = 2\n| nationalyears2 = 1997\u20131998\n| nationalteam2 = [[Spain national under-18 football team|Spain U18]]\n| nationalcaps2 = 10\n| nationalgoals2 = 0\n| nationalyears3 = 1999\n| nationalteam3 = [[Spain national under-20 football team|Spain U20]]\n| nationalcaps3 = 6\n| nationalgoals3 = 2\n| nationalyears4 = 1998\u20132001\n| nationalteam4 = [[Spain national under-21 football team|Spain U21]]\n| nationalcaps4 = 25\n| nationalgoals4 = 7\n| nationalyears5 = 2000\n| nationalteam5 = [[Spain national under-23 football team|Spain U23]]\n| nationalcaps5 = 6\n| nationalgoals5 = 2\n| nationalyears6 = 2000\u20132014\n| nationalteam6 = [[Spain national football team|Spain]]\n| nationalcaps6 = 133\n| nationalgoals6 = 13\n| nationalyears7 = 1998\u20132016\n| nationalteam7 = [[Catalonia national football team|Catalonia]]\n| nationalcaps7 = 12\n| nationalgoals7 = 2\n| manageryears1 = 2019\u2013\n| managerclubs1 = [[Al Sadd SC|Al Sadd]]\n| medaltemplates = \n{{MedalSport | Men's [[Association football|football]]}}\n{{MedalCountry|{{fb|ESP}}}}\n{{MedalCompetition|[[FIFA World Cup]]}}\n{{Medal|W|[[2010 FIFA World Cup|2010 South Africa]]|}}\n{{MedalCompetition|[[UEFA European Championship]]}}\n{{Medal|W|[[UEFA Euro 2008|2008 Austria\u2013Switzerland]]|}}\n{{Medal|W|[[UEFA Euro 2012|2012 Poland\u2013Ukraine]]|}}\n{{MedalCompetition|[[FIFA Confederations Cup]]}}\n{{Medal|3rd|[[2009 FIFA Confederations Cup|2009 South Africa]]|}}\n{{Medal|RU|[[2013 FIFA Confederations Cup|2013 Brazil]]|}}\n{{MedalCompetition|[[Football at the Summer Olympics|Summer Olympics]]}}\n{{Medal|2nd|[[2000 Summer Olympics|2000 Sydney]]|[[Football at the 2000 Summer Olympics|Team]]}}\n{{MedalCompetition|[[FIFA U-20 World Cup|FIFA World Youth Championship]]}}\n{{Medal|G|[[1999 FIFA World Youth Championship|1999 Nigeria]]|}}\n| club-update = \n| nationalteam-update = \n}}\n'''Xavier Hern\u00e1ndez Creus''' ({{IPA-ca|\u02c8\u0283a\u03b2i \u0259\u027e\u02c8nand\u0259s \u02c8k\u027e\u025bws|lang}}, {{IPA-es|\u02c8t\u0283a\u03b2j\u203fe\u027e\u02c8nande\u03b8 \u02c8k\u027eews|lang}}; born 25 January 1980), nicknamed '''Xavi''', is a Spanish [[Association football|football]] [[manager (association football)|manager]] and former player who is the manager of [[Qatar Stars League]] football club [[Al Sadd SC|Al Sadd]]. Highly regarded for his humble personality and team ethics, Xavi is viewed as being the embodiment of the ''[[tiki-taka]]'' passing style of play, and is widely considered to be one of the greatest central midfielders of all time.<ref name=\"ReferenceA\">{{cite web|url=http://www.goal.com/en-gb/news/3277/la-liga/2010/11/30/2238990/is-barcelona-star-xavi-the-best-centre-midfielder-of-all|title=Is Barcelona star Xavi the best centre midfielder of all time?|date=30 November 2010|publisher=Goal.com|accessdate=19 January 2014}}</ref><ref name=\"ReferenceB\">{{cite web|url=http://www.goal.com/en/news/1717/editorial/2009/05/28/1291105/cl-special-xavi-the-best-centre-midfielder-in-the-world-the|title=CL Special: Xavi \u2013 The Best Centre Midfielder In The World, The Symbol Of Pure Football|date=28 May 2009|publisher=Goal.com|accessdate=19 January 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://espnfc.com/player/_/id/12907/xavi-hern%C3%A1ndez-creus?cc=4716|title=Xavi Bio, Stats, News \u2013 Football|date=25 January 1980|publisher=ESPN|accessdate=19 January 2014}}</ref> He is also considered by many to be the greatest Spanish player ever.<ref>[https://uk.eurosport.yahoo.com/blogs/andy-mitten/xavi--spain-s-greatest-ever-footballer-171554241.html \"Xavi: Spain\u2019s greatest ever footballer?\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150611180944/https://uk.eurosport.yahoo.com/blogs/andy-mitten/xavi--spain-s-greatest-ever-footballer-171554241.html|date=11 June 2015}}. Eurosport. Retrieved 22 January 2016</ref><ref>[http://www.foxsports.com/soccer/story/sergio-busquets-xavi-is-spain-s-best-player-of-all-time-032815 \"Sergio Busquets: Xavi is Spain's best player of all time\"]. Fox Sports. Retrieved 22 January 2016</ref> \n\nXavi joined ''[[La Masia]]'', the [[FC Barcelona|Barcelona]] youth academy, at age 11, and made his first-team debut against [[RCD Mallorca|Mallorca]] in August 1998. In all, he played over 700 matches, a club record, and scored 85 goals. Xavi is the first player in the club's history to play 150 European and [[FIFA Club World Cup]] matches combined.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.fcbarcelona.com/football/first-team/detail/article/xavi-150-international-games-with-barca|title=Xavi, 150 international games with Bar\u00e7a |date=23 October 2012|publisher=[[FC Barcelona]]|accessdate=11 March 2015}}</ref> With Barcelona, Xavi won eight [[La Liga]] titles and four [[UEFA Champions League]] titles. He has won 31 trophies for Barcelona and Spain, a total only surpassed by [[Andr\u00e9s Iniesta]] as the most decorated Spanish player in history.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.fcbarcelona.com/football/first-team/detail/article/xavi-a-record-title-winner|title=Xavi \u2013 a record title winner|date=7 July 2012|accessdate=11 March 2015|publisher=[[FC Barcelona]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://news-football.net/overview-xavi-25-becomes-the-spanish-player-with-most-official-trophies-ever/|title=Overview: Xavi (25) becomes the Spanish player with most official trophies ever|date=30 August 2013|publisher=News-football.net|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140113161451/http://news-football.net/overview-xavi-25-becomes-the-spanish-player-with-most-official-trophies-ever/|archivedate=13 January 2014|accessdate=19 January 2014|url-status=dead}}</ref> Xavi came third in the 2009 [[FIFA World Player of the Year]], followed by third place for its successor award, the [[FIFA Ballon d'Or]], in [[2010 FIFA Ballon d'Or|2010]] and [[2011 FIFA Ballon d'Or|2011]]. In 2011, he was runner up to [[Lionel Messi]] for the [[UEFA Best Player in Europe Award]].\n\nWith Spain, Xavi won the [[U-20 World Cup|FIFA World Youth Championship]] in [[1999 FIFA World Youth Championship|1999]], and the Olympic silver medal at the [[Football at the 2000 Summer Olympics|2000 Olympics]]. After making his senior team debut in 2000, he was [[cap (sport)|capped]] 133 times for the [[Spain national football team|Spain national team]], and was an influential figure in the team's successes. He played an integral role in Spain's victory at the [[2010 FIFA World Cup]], as well as their wins at both [[UEFA Euro 2008]] and [[UEFA Euro 2012]]. He was named Player of the Tournament at UEFA Euro 2008,<ref name=\"UEFA 2008\">{{Cite news|url=http://en.euro2008.uefa.com/news/kind=1/newsid=729378.html#xavi+emerges+euros|title=Xavi emerges as EURO's top man|date=30 June 2008|publisher=[[UEFA]]|accessdate=20 April 2009|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090501220833/http://en.euro2008.uefa.com/news/kind=1/newsid=729378.html#xavi+emerges+euros|archivedate=1 May 2009}}</ref> and was named in the [[UEFA European Championship|UEFA Euro Team of the Tournament]] in 2008 and 2012. At UEFA Euro 2012, with his two assists in the [[UEFA Euro 2012 final|final]], Xavi became the first player to register assists in two separate UEFA Euro finals, having set up the only goal in the [[UEFA Euro 2008 Final|final]] four years earlier.<ref name=\"Goal.com\">{{cite news|url=http://www.goal.com/en/news/2898/euro-2012/2012/07/01/3204471/casillas-torres-xavi-amongst-record-breakers-for-spain|title=Casillas, Torres & Xavi amongst record-breakers for Spain|publisher=Goal.com|date=1 July 2012|accessdate=2 July 2012}}</ref> He had a 91% passing success rate at the [[2010 FIFA World Cup]] and was named in the World Cup All-Star Team. After the [[2014 FIFA World Cup]], Xavi announced his retirement from international football.<ref>{{Cite web|url = https://www.theguardian.com/football/2014/aug/05/xavi-retires-international-football-spain-barcelona|title = Spain midfielder Xavi announces his retirement from international football|date = |accessdate = |website = |publisher = |last = |first = }}</ref>\n\nXavi was awarded the [[International Federation of Football History & Statistics|IFFHS]] [[IFFHS World's Best Playmaker|World's Best Playmaker]] award four times: 2008, 2009, 2010, 2011. He was included in the [[UEFA Team of the Year]] five times (2008, 2009, 2010, 2011, 2012), and was included in the [[FIFPro World XI|FIFA FIFPro World XI]] on six occasions: 2008, 2009, 2010, 2011, 2012, 2013. Xavi was awarded the [[Prince of Asturias Awards|Prince of Asturias Award]] for Sports in 2012.\n\n==Early life==\n{{Quote box | width=27% | align=right| quote=\"I've been lucky enough to be brought up on the Barcelona ethos. Which has taught me the value of being part of a team. 'Today for you, tomorrow for me.' Those qualities are essential for life in general.\" |source =\u2014Xavi on learning the team ethos of Barcelona while at the club's youth system, ''[[La Masia]]''.<ref>\"Barcelona: Football's Greatest\" (2013). Pitch International LLP.</ref> }}\n\nBorn in [[Terrassa]], [[Province of Barcelona|Barcelona]], [[Catalonia]],<ref\nname=\"barcelonasite\">{{cite web|url=http://www.fcbarcelona.com/football/first-team/staff/players/xavi |title=Xavi \u2013 Xavier Hern\u00e1ndez Creus |publisher=[[FC Barcelona]] |accessdate=11 March 2015 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150228131333/http://www.fcbarcelona.com/football/first-team/staff/players/xavi |archivedate=28 February 2015 }}</ref> Xavi is a product of [[FC Barcelona]]'s ''[[La Masia]]'' youth system, which he joined at the age of 11. His father, Joaquim, was a former player for [[CE Sabadell FC|Sabadell]] in the [[La Liga|first division]].<ref>{{cite news|author=Jordi Quixano, El Pa\u00eds |url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2012/jun/04/euro-2012-spain-secrets-players |title=Euro 2012: Spain \u2013 the secrets behind the players|publisher=theguardian.com |date= 4 June 2012|accessdate=19 January 2014 |location=London}}</ref> Xavi made his way through the youth and reserve teams and was a key member of [[Josep Maria Gonzalvo]]'s [[FC Barcelona B|Barcelona B]] team that won promotion to the [[Segunda Divisi\u00f3n|Second Division]].\n\nAlthough he was initially inspired by compatriot playmaker [[Pep Guardiola]] at Barcelona,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.fourfourtwo.com/features/big-interview-xavi-inside-mind-a-football-genius|title=The big interview: Xavi \u2013 inside the mind of a football genius|publisher=FourFourTwo|author1=Andrew Murray|date=27 June 2016|accessdate=29 July 2016}}</ref> as a child Xavi also watched a lot of English football, and looked up to midfielders [[John Barnes (footballer)|John Barnes]], [[Paul Gascoigne]] and [[Matt Le Tissier]].<ref name=barnes>{{cite news|title=Barcelona playmaker Xavi on Gascoigne, Barnes and Le Tissier|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/30058904|accessdate=16 November 2014|work=BBC Sport|date=14 November 2014}}</ref>\n\n==Club career==\n\n===Barcelona===\n\n====1998\u20132001====\nXavi's progression through the teams earned him a first-team appearance in a [[Copa Catalunya]] match against [[UE Lleida|Lleida]] on 5 May 1998<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.webdelcule.com/partidos/pa1997-98.html |title=bar\u00e7a,partidos 1997/98 |publisher=Webdelcule.com |date= |accessdate=16 March 2016}}</ref> and he scored his first goal on 18 August 1998 in the [[1998 Supercopa, de Espa\u00f1a|Super Cup final]] against [[RCD Mallorca|Mallorca]]. His debut in [[La Liga]] came against [[Valencia CF|Valencia]] on 3 October 1998 in a 3\u20131 victory for Barcelona. Initially featuring intermittently both for the reserve and senior teams, Xavi scored the only goal in a 1\u20130 victory over [[Real Valladolid]] when Barcelona were in tenth position in the league. Sustained impressive performances meant that he became a key member of [[Louis van Gaal]]'s title-winning team, finishing his debut season with 26 matches played and being named 1999 La Liga Breakthrough Player of the Year. Xavi became Barcelona's principal playmaker after an injury to [[Pep Guardiola]] in the [[1999\u20132000 La Liga|1999\u20132000]] season.\n\n====2001\u20132003====\nIn these years, Barcelona was on the verge of bankruptcy and struggling to keep its place in La Liga's elite. Playing in the midfield, but with a more defensive role, Xavi made 20 assists and scored 7 goals in those two seasons. On 16 March 2002, he scored his first goal in ''[[El Cl\u00e1sico]]'' against [[Real Madrid CF|Real Madrid]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Xavi's 10 Greatest Moments at Barcelona |url=http://bleacherreport.com/articles/1861925-xavis-10-greatest-moments-at-barcelona |agency=Bleacher Report |date=12 June 2018}}</ref>\n\n====2004\u20132008====\nXavi was named the [[captain (association football)|vice-captain]] in the [[2004\u201305 FC Barcelona season|2004\u201305 season]], in which he helped Barcelona win [[2004\u201305 La Liga|La Liga]] and the [[2004 Supercopa de Espa\u00f1a|2004]] [[Supercopa de Espa\u00f1a]].<ref name=\"UEFA profile\"/> He was named La Liga Spanish Player of the Year in 2005.<ref name=\"UEFA profile\"/>\n\nIn the [[2005\u201306 FC Barcelona season|2005\u201306 season]], Xavi tore the [[ligament]]s in his left knee in training; he was out of action for four months but returned in April and was on the substitutes bench for Barcelona's win in the [[2006 UEFA Champions League Final|2006 Champions League final]] against [[Arsenal F.C.|Arsenal]]. He also won [[2005\u201306 La Liga|La Liga]] and the [[2005 Supercopa de Espa\u00f1a|Supercopa de Espa\u00f1a]] again.<ref name=\"UEFA profile\">[http://www.uefa.com/teamsandplayers/players/player=35018/profile/index.html \"Xavi Hern\u00e1ndez\"]. UEFA.com. Retrieved 17 May 2014</ref>\n\n====2008\u201309 season====\n{{Quote box | width=28% | align=right| quote=\"Xavi is a player who has the Barcelona DNA: someone who has the taste for good football, someone who is humble and someone who has loyalty to this club. From the first moment I saw him play, I knew he would become the brain behind Barcelona for many years to come.\" |source =\u2014Former Barcelona coach [[Pep Guardiola]], September 2008.<ref>[http://www.espnfc.com/player?id=12907&cc=5739 \"Xavi Profile\"]. ESPN. Retrieved 17 May 2014</ref>}}\n\nAfter being named Player of the Tournament at Euro 2008, Xavi spoke to [[FC Bayern Munich|Bayern Munich]] about a transfer, but newly appointed Barcelona coach Pep Guardiola convinced him that he was too important to the club to be allowed to leave.<ref>{{cite news |title=Pep talked me OUT of joining Bayern, says Barcelona midfield star Xavi |url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/sport/football/article-2540664/Barcelona-star-Xavi-reveals-talked-deal-Bayern-Munich-Pep-Guardiola.html |first=David |last=Kent |work=Daily Mail |date=16 January 2014 |accessdate=22 May 2014}}</ref>{{deprecated inline|certain=yes|date=September 2019}}\n\nHe was a main part of Barcelona's treble and scored the fourth goal in the 4\u20131 win in the [[2009 Copa del Rey Final]] against [[Athletic Bilbao]], with a free kick. In [[2008\u201309 La Liga|La Liga]], one of his most significant games was the 6\u20132 ''Cl\u00e1sico'' victory over Real Madrid on 2 May; he assisted four goals \u2013 once to [[Carles Puyol]], once to [[Thierry Henry]] and twice to [[Lionel Messi]].\n\nXavi helped Barcelona win the [[2009 UEFA Champions League Final|2009 Champions League final]] 2\u20130 against [[Manchester United F.C.|Manchester United]], assisting the second goal by crossing to Messi for his header.<ref>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/europe/8060878.stm \"Barcelona 2\u20130 Man Utd\"]. BBC. Retrieved 17 May 2014</ref> Prior to the match, Manchester United coach [[Alex Ferguson|Sir Alex Ferguson]] heaped praise on the central midfield combination of Xavi and [[Andr\u00e9s Iniesta]], stating, \"I don't think Xavi and Iniesta have ever given the ball away in their lives. They get you on that carousel and they can leave you dizzy.\"<ref>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/europe/8052705.stm \"The men who make Barca beautiful\"]. BBC. Retrieved 17 May 2014</ref> Xavi was voted \"UEFA Champions League best midfielder\" for his contribution during Barcelona's victorious [[2008\u201309 UEFA Champions League|2008\u201309 Champions League campaign]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.uefa.com/memberassociations/news/newsid=1639472.html |title=UEFA Club Football Awards |publisher=UEFA.com |date=1 May 2011 |accessdate=19 January 2014}}</ref>\n\nXavi was the highest assisting player in La Liga with 20,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://espnfc.com/stats/assists/_/league/esp.1/year/2008/spanish-primera-division?cc=3888 |title=Spanish La Liga Assists Leaders \u2013 2008\u201309 |publisher=Espn Fc |date=31 May 2009 |accessdate=19 January 2014}}</ref> and in the Champions League, with 7; he earned 29 assists overall that season. Xavi was under contract to Bar\u00e7a until 2014 after extending his contract during the 2008\u201309 season.<ref name=\"rte\"/> The new contract made him one of the club's biggest earners, with a salary of \u20ac7.5&nbsp;million a year.<ref name=\"rte\">[http://www.rte.ie/sport/soccer/european/2008/1219/242632-barcelona/ \"Xavi extends Barcelona contract\"]. RTE. Retrieved 17 May 2014</ref>\n\n====2009\u201310 season====\n[[File:Xavi Joan Gamper 2008.jpg|thumb|Xavi in action for Barcelona in 2008.]]\nDuring the [[2009\u201310 FC Barcelona season|2009\u201310 season]], journalists increasingly noted Xavi's contribution to the Barcelona team. For example:\n{{quote|\"Quite simply the best midfielder of modern football. It could even be argued that Xavi and [[Lothar Matth\u00e4us|Matth\u00e4us]] are the two best in this position in history. World class for several years now, it is the past three seasons in particular where the 30-year-old has been untouchable. Xavi\u2019s passing is up there with [[Michel Platini]], he creates countless goals with genius through balls while virtually never relinquishing possession.\"<ref>Garganese, Carlo (April 19, 2010). \"Inter-Barcelona All Time Greatest XI\". Goal. Retrieved 19 April 2010</ref>}}\n\nIn the 2009\u201310 season, Xavi again topped the assists table and provided both the assists in Barcelona's 2\u20130 victory against Real Madrid at the [[Santiago Bernab\u00e9u Stadium]]. Barcelona won the [[2009\u201310 La Liga|Liga title]] with a record 99 points, and Xavi was acclaimed Barcelona's second-best player in a season-long vote.<ref>[https://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/football/european/7732621/Barcelona-players-hailed-for-La-Liga-title-win-but-Pep-Guardiola-feels-hard-done-by.html \"Barcelona players hailed for La Liga title win but Pep Guardiola feels hard done by\"]. The Telegraph. Retrieved 17 May 2014</ref> On 3 June 2010, [[Madrid]]-based newspaper ''[[Marca (newspaper)|Marca]]'' awarded him third place in the annual [[Trofeo Alfredo di St\u00e9fano]] award for the best player in La Liga, behind Lionel Messi and [[Cristiano Ronaldo]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.goal.com/en/news/12/spain/2010/06/03/1957099/barcelona-star-lionel-messi-wins-the-trofeo-alfredo-di |title=Barcelona Star Lionel Messi Wins The Trofeo Alfredo Di Stefano |publisher=Goal.com |date=3 June 2010 |accessdate=15 June 2010}}</ref>\n\n====2010\u201311 season====\n{{Quote box | width=27% | align=right| quote=\"Our model was imposed by [Johan] Cruyff; it's an Ajax model. It's all about rondos [piggy in the middle]. Rondo, rondo, rondo\"|source =\u2014Xavi speaking in 2011 about ''[[tiki-taka]]'' style of play introduced to the club by Dutch legend [[Johan Cruyff]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2011/feb/11/xavi-barcelona-spain-interview |title= I'm a romantic, says Xavi, heartbeat of Barcelona and Spain |publisher=The Guardian |last=Lowe |first=Sid |quote=Xavi Hern\u00e1ndez: \"Our model was imposed by [Johan] Cruyff; it's an Ajax model. It's all about rondos [piggy in the middle]. Rondo, rondo, rondo.\" |date=11 February 2011 |accessdate=12 June 2014}}</ref>}}\n\nOn 9 June 2010, Xavi signed a new four-year contract with the club, which could be automatically renewed up to 30 June 2016 based on number of games played.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.fcbarcelona.com/web/english/noticies/futbol/temporada09-10/06/09/n100609111479.html|archive-url=https://archive.is/20121208190603/http://www.fcbarcelona.com/web/english/noticies/futbol/temporada09-10/06/09/n100609111479.html|url-status=dead|archive-date=8 December 2012|title=Xavi extends deal until 2016|date=9 June 2010|accessdate=27 June 2010|publisher=FC Barcelona}}</ref> On 29 November, he scored his third goal against arch-rivals Real Madrid in a 5\u20130 home win. On 18 December, he scored another goal against [[RCD Espanyol|Espanyol]] in a 1\u20135 win. In the [[2010\u201311 UEFA Champions League|Champions League]], Xavi scored a valuable goal with an assist from [[David Villa]] in a home win against Arsenal, that saw Barcelona progress to the quarter-finals.<ref>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/europe/9416255.stm \"Barcelona 3 \u2013 1 Arsenal\"]. BBC Sport. Retrieved 25 May 2014</ref>\n\nXavi was one of the three finalists for the [[2010 FIFA Ballon d'Or]], and finished third in the vote behind his Barcelona teammates Lionel Messi and Andr\u00e9s Iniesta.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2010/dec/06/ballon-dor-messi-xavi-iniesta-barcelona |title=Lionel Messi, Xavi and Andr\u00e9s Iniesta shortlisted for Ballon d'Or |newspaper=[[The Guardian]] |date=6 December 2010 |accessdate=13 December 2010 |location=London}}</ref><ref>[https://www.fifa.com/ballondor/fifaballondor/player=229397/index.html] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101209141743/http://www.fifa.com/ballondor/fifaballondor/player=229397/index.html|date=9 December 2010}}</ref> He narrowly defeated Messi to win the Player of the Year award from ''[[World Soccer (magazine)|World Soccer]]'' magazine.<ref>[http://www.rsssf.com/miscellaneous/wsoc-awards.html \"World Soccer Awards\"] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160102073728/http://www.rsssf.com/miscellaneous/wsoc-awards.html |date=2 January 2016 }}. Rsssf. Retrieved 25 May 2014</ref>\n\nOn 2 January 2011, in a league match against [[Levante UD|Levante]], Xavi made his 549th appearance for the club in all competitions, matching the record held by [[Migueli]]. Xavi later became the player with the most appearances for Barcelona of all time.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.fcbarcelona.cat/web/english/noticies/futbol/temporada10-11/01/02/n110102114899.html |archive-url=https://archive.is/20120801211847/http://www.fcbarcelona.cat/web/english/noticies/futbol/temporada10-11/01/02/n110102114899.html |url-status=dead |archive-date=1 August 2012 |title=Xavi: \"I feel privileged\" |publisher=FC Barcelona |date=2 January 2011 |accessdate=2 January 2011 }}</ref> On 28 May, Xavi was imperious in the [[2011 UEFA Champions League Final]] at [[Wembley Stadium]] in [[London]] as Barcelona defeated Manchester United in the showpiece for the second time in three seasons, winning 3\u20131.<ref name=\"UEFA profile\"/>\n\n====2011\u201312 season====\n[[File:Puyol Xavi Messi FC Barcelona Team of the Year 2011.jpg|thumb|right|Xavi (middle) with Barcelona teammates [[Carles Puyol]] (left) and [[Lionel Messi]] (right) in December 2011]]\nXavi began the [[2011\u201312 FC Barcelona season|2011\u201312 season]] in fine goalscoring form and seemed to grow in his influence of the team despite the long-anticipated return of [[Cesc F\u00e0bregas]] and the promotion of [[Thiago Alc\u00e2ntara|Thiago]] to create added competition for places in ''Bar\u00e7a'''s attacking midfield positions.\n\nOn 18 December, in the [[2011 FIFA Club World Cup Final]] in [[Yokohama]], Barcelona won 4\u20130 against Brazilian side [[Santos FC|Santos]] as Xavi scored a goal and made an assist to Lionel Messi.<ref name=\"FIFA final\">[https://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/football/competitions/la-liga/8963955/Barcelona-v-Santos-Fifa-Club-World-Cup-final-live.html \"Barcelona v Santos: Fifa Club World Cup final live\"]. The Telegraph. Retrieved 17 May 2014</ref> After the ball was slightly behind him, Xavi brought the ball down with a cocked leg, effectively using his ankle to control it, before slipping a pass through to Messi, who scored the first goal.<ref name=\"FIFA final\"/>\n\nXavi scored the winning goal in the Group H game against [[A.C. Milan|Milan]], a vital match for Barcelona's progression in the [[2011\u201312 UEFA Champions League|UEFA Champions League]]. In total, Xavi had the best goalscoring return of his career in 2011\u201312 season with ten Liga goals, two in the [[2011\u201312 Copa del Rey|Copa del Rey]] \u2013 which Barcelona won \u2013 and one in the Club World Cup final win.<ref name=\"UEFA profile\"/>\n\n====2012\u201313 season====\n[[File:2012 2013 - 06 Xavi Hern\u00e1ndez.jpg|thumb|200px|right|Xavi as Barcelona captain in November 2012]]\nOn 18 December 2012, Barcelona renewed Xavi\u2019s contract, extending it until 30 June 2016.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.fcbarcelona.com/football/first-team/detail/article/carles-puyol-xavi-hernandez-and-leo-messi-renew-their-contract-with-fc-barcelona|title=Bar\u00e7a has renewed the contracts of Carles Puyol, Xavi Hern\u00e1ndez and Leo Messi|date=18 December 2012|accessdate=8 January 2013|publisher=FC Barcelona Official Website}}</ref>\nHe scored a goal against Real Madrid in a 3\u20132 win for Barcelona. Xavi was named in the [[FIFPro World XI|FIFA World XI]], along with teammates Iniesta, Messi and [[Dani Alves]].<ref>[https://www.fifa.com/ballondor/news/newsid=1979448/ \"FIFA/FIFPro World XI 2012\"]. FIfA.com. Retrieved 25 May 2014</ref> Barcelona had virtually secured their [[2012\u201313 La Liga|La Liga title]] by the start of 2013, eventually equalling Real Madrid's 100-point record of the previous season.<ref>{{cite news |first=Sid |last=Lowe |title=A Sense of Anticlimax but Barcelona Still Deserve Their La Liga Title |newspaper=The Guardian |date=13 May 2013 |url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/blog/2013/may/13/barcelona-title-anti-climax |accessdate=9 August 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |first=Sid |last=Lowe |title=Barcelona Face up to Uncomfortable Truths after Alarming Slump in Form |newspaper=The Guardian |date=9 March 2013 |url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/blog/2013/mar/09/barcelona-slump-tito-vilanova |accessdate=9 August 2015}}</ref>\n\n====2013\u201314 season====\nOn 16 January 2014, Xavi made his 700th appearance for the first team against [[Getafe CF|Getafe]] in the [[2013\u201314 Copa del Rey|Copa del Rey]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.fcbarcelona.com/football/first-team/detail/article/xavi-hernandez-features-in-his-700th-official-match-for-fc-barcelona|title=Xavi Hern\u00e1ndez features in his 700th official match for FC Barcelona|date=16 January 2014|accessdate=16 January 2014|publisher=FC Barcelona Official Website}}</ref> For the first time in five years, Barcelona ended the season without a major trophy; they were [[2014 Copa del Rey Final|defeated in the Copa del Rey final]] by Real Madrid with [[Gareth Bale]] scoring a late winner, and [[2013\u201314 La Liga|lost the league]] in the last game to Atl\u00e9tico Madrid.<ref>{{cite web |title=Barcelona's Lionel Messi: I Had a Lot of Problems during 2013\u201314 Season |publisher=ESPN FC |date=19 February 2014 |url=http://www.espnfc.com/barcelona/story/2306392/barcelona-lionel-messi-i-had-a-lot-of-problems-during-2013-14-season |accessdate=10 August 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Barcelona Name Luis Enrique as New Coach, Lionel Messi Signs New Contract with La Liga Club |publisher=ABC News |date=21 May 2014 |url=http://www.abc.net.au/news/2014-05-20/luis-enrique-new-barca-coach-as-messi-re-signs/5463692 |accessdate=10 August 2015}}</ref>\n\n====2014\u201315 season====\nIn June 2014, it was announced that Xavi would be leaving the club.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.sportal.com.au/football/news/alves-confirms-xavi-departure/1nwylwpzlx0bs1vx9f0r10gbil |title=Alves confirms Xavi departure |date=25 June 2014 |work=Sportal.com.au |accessdate=26 June 2014 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140628221231/http://www.sportal.com.au/football/news/alves-confirms-xavi-departure/1nwylwpzlx0bs1vx9f0r10gbil |archivedate=28 June 2014 }}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url = http://www.insidespanishfootball.com/113611/alves-its-true-xavi-is-leaving-barca/|title = Alves: It\u2019s true, Xavi is leaving Bar\u00e7a|date = 25 June 2014|work = Inside Spanish Football|accessdate = 26 June 2014|url-status = dead|archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20140627190402/http://www.insidespanishfootball.com/113611/alves-its-true-xavi-is-leaving-barca/|archivedate = 27 June 2014|df = dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url = http://www.marca.com/2014/06/21/en/football/barcelona/1403335502.html|title = Xavi confirms Camp Nou exit|last = |first = |date = 6 June 2014|work = Marca.com \u00bb English|accessdate = 26 June 2014}}</ref> On 22 July, however, after talks with newly appointed manager and former teammate [[Luis Enrique (footballer)|Luis Enrique]], Xavi decided to stay at [[Camp Nou]] for one more season.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.goal.com/en/news/11/transfer-zone/2014/07/22/4975988/barcelona-convince-xavi-to-stay|title=Barcelona convince Xavi to stay|publisher=Goal.com|date=22 July 2014|accessdate=23 July 2014}}</ref> He was also appointed as club captain. On 25 April 2015, Xavi made his 500th La Liga appearance, becoming the eighth player in history to do so.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.fcbarcelona.com/football/first-team/detail/article/xavi-makes-500th-liga-appearance|title=Xavi makes 500th Liga appearance|publisher=FCBarcelona.com|date=25 April 2015|accessdate=25 April 2015}}</ref> On 4 June, a farewell event was held at Barcelona for Xavi with players, managers, friends and family paying tribute to him.<ref>{{cite web|url= https://www.bbc.com/sport/0/football/32994478|title=Champions League: Barcelona's Xavi breaks down in live TV tribute|date=3 June 2015|work=BBC Sport|accessdate=4 June 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url= http://www.uefa.com/uefachampionsleague/news/newsid=2253556.html|title=Infographic: Xavi's 150|date=3 June 2015|work=UEFA.com|accessdate=4 June 2015}}</ref>\n\nOn 6 June 2015, Xavi came on as a 78th-minute substitute for Andr\u00e9s Iniesta to make his final appearance for Barcelona during the [[2015 UEFA Champions League Final|Champions League final]], as the club won its fifth [[European Champion Clubs' Cup|European Cup]], beating [[Juventus F.C.|Juventus]] at [[Berlin]]'s [[Olympiastadion (Berlin)|Olympiastadion]]. Xavi, as club captain, lifted the trophy.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.uefa.com/uefachampionsleague/season=2015/matches/round=2000552/match=2015227/postmatch/report/index.html|title=Barcelona see off Juventus to claim fifth title|date=6 June 2015|work=UEFA}}</ref> This made Barcelona the first club in history to win [[Treble (association football)|the treble]] of domestic league, domestic cup and European Cup twice.<ref name=triple>{{cite news|url=http://www.fcbarcelona.com/football/first-team/detail/article/barca-make-history-with-second-treble|title=Bar\u00e7a make history with second treble!|date=6 June 2015|work=FC Barcelona}}</ref> Xavi, Iniesta, Messi, [[Gerard Piqu\u00e9]], [[Pedro (footballer, born July 1987)|Pedro]], [[Sergio Busquets]] and [[Dani Alves]] were part of both treble-winning teams.<ref name=triple/>\n\n===Al-Sadd===\n[[File:Xavi in Persepolis FC and Al sadd Match.jpg|thumb|Xavi playing for [[Al Sadd SC|Al Sadd]] against [[Persepolis F.C.|Persepolis]] in April 2018.]]\nOn 21 May 2015, Xavi announced that he would join Qatari club [[Al Sadd SC|Al Sadd]] at the end of the [[2014\u201315 FC Barcelona season|2014\u201315 season]] on a three-year contract. According to his agent, the deal would involve him becoming an ambassador for the [[2022 FIFA World Cup]] in the country, and also start his coaching qualifications.<ref>{{cite news|title=Barcelona's Xavi poised to join Qatar side Al Sadd|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/32811382|accessdate=21 May 2015|work=BBC Sport|date=20 May 2015}}</ref> He made his debut for Al-Sadd in a 4\u20130 win over [[Al-Mesaimeer Sports Club|Mesaimeer]] on 13 September 2015, assisting in the team's first goal.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.marca.com/en/2015/09/13/en/football/international_football/1442181379.html|title=Xavi on hand with assist on Qatar debut|publisher=MARCA|author=Juan Castro|date=13 September 2015|accessdate=14 September 2015}}</ref> In the following match, he scored his first goal for the club in a 2\u20132 draw with [[Umm Salal SC|Umm Salal]].<ref name=\"Xavi Goal\">{{cite web|last1=Bailey|first1=Ryan|title=Xavi first Goal|url=http://bleacherreport.com/articles/2568395-xavi-scores-his-first-goal-for-al-sadd|website=Bleacher Report|publisher=Bleacher Report|accessdate=14 May 2016|ref=53}}</ref> Al Sadd ended the league campaign in third position putting them in a place for the next season's [[AFC Champions League]]. Xavi scored three goals during the season. In the Champions League, Al Sadd were knocked out from the qualifying rounds by Emirati side [[Al Jazira Club|Al Jazira]] on penalties; Xavi missed his spot kick.\n\nXavi won his first trophy with Al Sadd following a 2\u20131 victory over [[El Jaish SC|El Jaish]] in the [[Qatar Cup]] final on 29 April 2017.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.goal.com/en-gb/news/683/main/2017/04/30/35080202/xavi-wins-first-trophy-with-al-sadd?ICID=OP|title=Xavi wins first trophy with Al Sadd|date=30 April 2017|work=Goal.com}}</ref> On 10 November 2017, Xavi said that he would retire when his contract with Al Sadd expired at the end of the [[2017\u201318 Qatar Stars League|2017\u201318 season]], and would later pursue a coaching career.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/41941578|title=Xavi: Ex-Barcelona & Spain midfielder to retire at end of season|date=10 November 2017|work=BBC Sport|access-date=11 November 2017|language=en-GB}}</ref> However, he postponed these plans and signed a two-year contract extension on 24 May 2018.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://al-saddclub.com/news/football/official-xavi-extends-stay-at-al-sadd-until-2020/|title=OFFICIAL: Xavi extends stay at Al-Sadd until 2020\n|date=24 May 2018|publisher=Al Sadd Club|access-date=24 May 2018|language=en-GB}}</ref>\n\nOn 2 May 2019, Xavi announced that he would be retiring from professional football at the end of the season.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/48138914|title=Ex-Barcelona and Spain midfielder Xavi to retire at end of season|website=BBC Sport|date=2 May 2019}}</ref> On 20 May 2019, Xavi played the final match of his career, a 2\u20130 defeat to [[Persepolis F.C.|Persepolis]] in [[Tehran]], which was Al Sadd's final [[2019 AFC Champions League|AFC Champions League]] group match; before the match, he stated that he would like to remain in Qatar after his retirement, and that he would look to begin a coaching career, commenting: \"The idea is to start as a coach in Qatar, to test myself and get some experience.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.the-afc.com/competitions/afc-champions-league/latest/news/legend-xavi-bids-farewell |title=Legend Xavi bids farewell |publisher=www.the-afc.com |date=21 May 2019 |accessdate=1 August 2019 }}</ref>\n\n==International career==\n[[File:Xavier Hern\u00e1ndez - Spain vs. Chile, 10th September 2013.jpg|thumb|upright|Xavi playing for Spain.]]\nXavi played for [[Spain national football team|Spain]] at the [[Football at the 2000 Summer Olympics|2000 Olympics]], [[2002 FIFA World Cup|2002 World Cup]], [[UEFA Euro 2004|Euro 2004]], [[2006 FIFA World Cup|2006 World Cup]], [[UEFA Euro 2008|Euro 2008]], [[2009 FIFA Confederations Cup|2009 Confederations Cup]], [[2010 FIFA World Cup|2010 World Cup]], [[UEFA Euro 2012|Euro 2012]], [[2013 FIFA Confederations Cup|2013 Confederations Cup]] and the [[2014 FIFA World Cup|2014 World Cup]].\n\n===UEFA Euro 2008===\nXavi was named Euro 2008's [[UEFA Euro 2008#Awards|player of the tournament]] after Spain defeated [[Germany national football team|Germany]] 1\u20130 in the final.<ref name=\"Xavi 2008\"/> Xavi was dominant in midfield, where his passing and reading of the game was pivotal to Spain's success, as he led his nation to their first silverware since the [[UEFA Euro 1964|1964 European Championship]].<ref name=\"Xavi 2008\">[http://www.uefa.com/uefaeuro/season=2008/history-maker/ \"Xavi on Spain's victory for the little guy\"]. UEFA.com. Retrieved 17 May 2014</ref> [[Andy Roxburgh]], head of [[UEFA]]'s Technical Committee, said, \"We have chosen Xavi because he epitomizes the Spanish style of play. He was influential in the whole possession, passing and penetrating kind of game that Spain played.\"<ref name=\"UEFA 2008\"/>\n\nXavi scored the first goal in the semi-final against [[Russia national football team|Russia]], which Spain won 3\u20130. In the [[UEFA Euro 2008 Final|final]], he made the pass from which [[Fernando Torres]] scored the winning goal.<ref>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/euro_2008/7363545.stm \"Germany 0\u20131 Spain.\"]. BBC. Retrieved 29 May 2014</ref>\n\n===2010 World Cup===\n[[File:Xavi Hern\u00e1ndez Spain 2009.jpg|thumb|upright|Xavi at the 2010 FIFA World Cup.]]\nXavi was named in Spain's squad for the [[2010 FIFA World Cup|2010 World Cup]] in South Africa, with Spain eventually winning their first [[FIFA World Cup|World Cup]].<ref>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/world_cup_2010/matches/match_64 \"Netherlands 0\u20131 Spain\"]. BBC. Retrieved 29 May 2014</ref> He provided the most number of accurate passes, 599 with a passing success rate of 91%, and he crossed the ball inside the 18-yard box more than any other player in the tournament. In the final he made 57 accurate forward half passes.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www-958.ibm.com/software/data/cognos/manyeyes/files/thumbnails/8d41dba8-8d43-11df-a224-000255111976.wm.png |title=Accurate Forward Half Passes in World Cup Final 2010 |publisher=[[FIFA]] |date=23 August 2010 |accessdate=7 January 2011}}</ref> Xavi also covered 80.20 kilometres throughout the competitions, averaging approximately 11.5 kilometres per game.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.fifa.com/worldcup/archive/southafrica2010/statistics/players/distanceandspeed.html |title=Distance |publisher=[[FIFA]] |date=24 August 2010 |accessdate=9 January 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20101211011708/http://www.fifa.com/worldcup/archive/southafrica2010/statistics/players/distanceandspeed.html |archivedate=11 December 2010 }}</ref> In the [[2010 FIFA World Cup Final|final]], he covered a distance of almost 15 kilometres.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.fifa.com/mm/document/tournament/competition/01/27/28/20/64_0711_ned-esp_playersheatmap.pdf|title=Players Heat Map |publisher=[[FIFA]] |date=26 August 2010 |accessdate=12 January 2011}}</ref>\n\n{{Quote|Xavi is the beating heart of this Spanish team, the man dictating the tiki-taka pulse of pass after pass. He may be just 5ft 7in with a curiously hunched gait but no player more influences the way his whole team plays. He doesn't score, doesn't really tackle: he just passes and passes with a precision and wit unmatched by any of his peers.|Duncan White of ''[[The Daily Telegraph|The Telegraph]]'' on Xavi at the 2010 World Cup.<ref name=\"White Telegraph\"/>}}\n\nDuring the round of 16 match against [[Portugal national football team|Portugal]], Xavi provided a backheel pass in the 63rd minute to David Villa. Although Villa had his shot with his left foot blocked by goalkeeper [[Eduardo Carvalho|Eduardo]], he then put in the rebound with his right foot for the winning goal.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.fifa.com/worldcup/archive/southafrica2010/matches/round=249717/match=300061498/report.html |title=Spain \u2013 Portugal |publisher=[[FIFA]] |date=27 August 2010 |accessdate=13 January 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110116092811/http://www.fifa.com/worldcup/archive/southafrica2010/matches/round=249717/match=300061498/report.html |archivedate=16 January 2011 }}</ref> In the semi-final against Germany, Xavi crossed from a corner to the edge of the six-yard box, where Carles Puyol scored with a header into the top-right corner.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.fifa.com/worldcup/archive/southafrica2010/matches/round=249719/match=300111114/report.html |title=Germany \u2013 Spain |publisher=[[FIFA]] |date=28 August 2010 |accessdate=14 January 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110212010127/http://www.fifa.com/worldcup/archive/southafrica2010/matches/round=249719/match=300111114/report.html |archivedate=12 February 2011 }}</ref>\n\n===UEFA Euro 2012===\n[[File:Xavi and Riccardo Montolivo Euro 2012 final.jpg|thumb|left|upright|Xavi (left) turns away from [[Italy national football team|Italy]]'s [[Riccardo Montolivo]] in the [[UEFA Euro 2012 Final|Euro 2012 final]]]]\n\nXavi played for Spain at Euro 2012 which Spain won by defeating Italy 4\u20130 in the [[UEFA Euro 2012 Final|final]]. Xavi attempted 136 passes (127 completed, 94% success rate) during Spain's 4\u20130 victory in the group stage match against the [[Republic of Ireland national football team|Republic of Ireland]], more than any other player in a [[UEFA European Championship|European Championship]] match. The previous record of 117 had been set by [[Ronald Koeman]] in a [[UEFA Euro 1992|Euro 1992]] match between the [[Netherlands national football team|Netherlands]] and [[Denmark national football team|Denmark]]. Xavi and Andr\u00e9s Iniesta made 229 passes in the match, more than the combined Irish team managed. \"Pum, pum, pum, pum\" was how Xavi described the rhythmic sound of the ball moving between himself and his midfield partner.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/football/teams/spain/9366987/Euro-2012-Spains-dynamic-duo-of-Xavi-and-Andres-Iniesta-have-broken-the-mould-proving-size-doesnt-matter.html|title=Spain's dynamic duo of Xavi and Andres Iniesta have broken the mould proving size doesn't matter|date=9 July 2012|accessdate=9 July 2012|location=London|work=The Daily Telegraph|first=Paul|last=Hayward}}</ref>\n\nWith Xavi providing two assists in the final, for [[Jordi Alba]] and Fernando Torres, he became the first player to register assists in two European Championship finals.<ref name=\"Goal.com\"/> Spain's UEFA Euro 2012 victory made Xavi the most decorated player in Spanish football history, a status that he previously shared with Carles Puyol, who missed the tournament.<ref name=\"Goal.com\"/>\n\n===Retirement===\nOn 5 August 2014, following the 2014 World Cup where Spain were eliminated at the group stage, Xavi announced his retirement from international football, having made 133 appearances in a 14-year period.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.goal.com/en/news/12/spain/2014/08/05/5007661/xavi-retires-from-international-football|title=Xavi retires from international football|date=5 August 2014|accessdate=11 March 2015|publisher=Goal.com|first = Ben|last = Hayward}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url = https://www.bbc.com/sport/0/football/28654486|title = Xavi Hernandez: Barcelona legend quits Spain duty|last = |first = |date = 5 August 2014|access-date = 11 March 2015|work = BBC Sport}}</ref> Spain's World Cup-winning manager [[Vicente del Bosque]] paid tribute, stating that Xavi was \"a key part of the team's style of play\" and \"he was more important to us than even the manager\", also adding, \"We will miss him both on and off the pitch. He is a player who we hold in great esteem both personally and as a player. He is and always will be a person and a player who is greatly valued by the [[Royal Spanish Football Federation|federation]], the coaching staff and by myself.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url = http://www.dailymail.co.uk/sport/football/article-2717867/Xavi-important-Spain-s-success-says-Vicente-del-Bosque.html|title = Xavi is even more important to Spain's success than me, says Vicente del Bosque|date = 6 August 2014|accessdate = 11 March 2015|website = Daily Mail|publisher = |last = Upal|first = Sunni}}</ref>{{deprecated inline|certain=yes|date=September 2019}}\n\n== Managerial career ==\n\n=== Al-Sadd ===\n[[File:Xavi 13981129001173637176665956870909.jpg|thumb|upright|Xavi managing Al-Sadd in an [[AFC Champions League]] match against [[Sepahan F.C.|Sepahan]], 18 February 2020]]\nOn 28 May 2019, it was announced that Xavi would take over as manager of Al-Sadd on a two-year contract.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://twitter.com/AlsaddSC/status/1133352007924944896|title=OFFICIAL: #Xavi Hernandez will take over as the head coach of #AlSadd from the beginning of the next season! #Qatar|last=\u0627\u0644\u0633\u062f|first=AlSadd S. C. {{!}} \u0646\u0627\u062f\u064a|date=28 May 2019|website=@AlsaddSC|language=en|access-date=28 May 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.goal.com/en-qa/news/barcelona-legend-xavi-appointed-manager-of-qatar-based-al/o8mfc0yg87me1v5he990dtroj|title=Barcelona legend Xavi appointed manager of Qatar-based club {{!}} Goal.com|website=www.goal.com|language=en|access-date=28 May 2019}}</ref> Xavi helped the club reach the semi-finals of the [[2019 AFC Champions League|AFC Champions League]], where they were eliminated by [[Al-Hilal FC]] 6\u20135 on aggregate.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.foxsportsasia.com/football/1188928/afc-champions-league-al-hilal-2-4-al-sadd-6-5-agg-xavis-side-fall-just-short-in-comeback-bid/ |title=AFC Champions League: Al-Hilal 2-4 Al Sadd (6-5 agg): Xavi\u2019s side fall just short in comeback bid |publisher=Fox Sports Asia |date=22 October 2019 |accessdate=23 October 2019 }}</ref>\n<br />\n\n==Style of play==\n{{Quote box | width=27% | align=left| quote=\"I think I haven't changed at all to what I am now. I've been a passer since a young age. I liked passing with the rest of the players and my friends when we played football on the streets, in the main square, and at school. I think I was very similar to what people see in the stadium.\"|source= Xavi on his own style of play, November 2014.<ref name=barnes/>}} \nXavi is widely considered as one of the best central midfielders of all-time,<ref name=\"ReferenceA\"/><ref name=\"ReferenceB\"/><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.sbnation.com/soccer/2017/11/29/16643336/xavi-retirement-fc-barcelona-best-midfielder|title=Xavi was the best midfielder to ever play|last=Madu|first=Zito|date=29 November 2017|website=SBNation.com|language=en|access-date=12 January 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://bleacherreport.com/articles/502011-top-10-all-time-barcelona-midfielders-where-do-xavi-and-iniesta-rank|title=Top 10 All-Time Barcelona Midfielders: Do Xavi and Iniesta Make The Grade?|last=Sebastian|first=Adi-Oula|website=Bleacher Report|language=en|access-date=12 January 2020}}</ref> relying largely on his ability to find and exploit space as a [[playmaker]]. As he said, \"That's what I do: look for spaces. All day. I'm always looking.\"<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2011/feb/11/xavi-barcelona-spain-interview | title=I'm a romantic, says Xavi, heartbeat of Barcelona and Spain | work=The Guardian | last=Lowe | first=Sid | date=10 February 2011 | accessdate=14 December 2011 | location=London}}</ref> Finding space, he would appear for a teammate to receive and then move the ball on, with his coach Pep Guardiola putting it: \"I get the ball, I give the ball, I get the ball, I give the ball.\" A diminutive, agile, and technically skilled player, with a slender physique, Xavi\u2019s signature move when in possession involved him performing a 360 degree turn, a [[Dummy (football)|feint]] known as ''la pelopina'', that allowed him to [[Dribbling#Association football|move away from the opposing player]], retain possession, and gave him space and time on the ball to think about his next pass, which compensated for his lack of pace.<ref name=\"White Telegraph\">{{cite news |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/football/teams/spain/7883318/World-Cup-final-Holland-must-stop-Xavi-to-stop-Spain.html |title=World Cup final: Holland must stop Xavi to stop Spain |work=The Telegraph |date=11 June 2018 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.football-espana.net/69073/xavi-tiki-taka-saved-me-valverde |title=Xavi: Tiki-taka saved me, Valverde\u2026 |publisher=Football Espa\u00f1a |date=24 December 2017 |accessdate=30 July 2019 }}</ref><ref name=\"Most Skilled Passers in World Football History\">{{cite web |url=https://bleacherreport.com/articles/1634018-25-most-skilled-passers-in-world-football-history#slide12 |title=25 Most Skilled Passers in World Football History |publisher=Bleacher Report |last1=Towle |first1=Max |date=9 May 2013 |accessdate=30 July 2019 }}</ref><ref name=\"metronomic\">{{cite news |url=https://www.irishtimes.com/sport/soccer/champions-league/xavi-and-pirlo-metronomic-men-who-defined-a-generation-1.2238958 |title=Xavi and Pirlo: metronomic men who defined a generation |work=The Irish Times |last1=Fitzpatrick |first1=Richard |date=6 June 2015 |accessdate=30 July 2019 }}</ref>\n\nXavi's outstanding vision, pinpoint accurate passing, excellent off the ball movement, superb reading of the game, and world-class ball control allowed him to create chances for teammates and dictate the flow of play in midfield, while rarely relinquishing possession, as displayed by his performance during Spain's 2010 World Cup victory, where he maintained a 91% passing success rate throughout the entire tournament.<ref name=\"Xavi 2008\"/><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/football/babb/11618815/Xavi-The-greatest-midfielder-of-a-generation.html |title=Xavi: The greatest midfielder of a generation |work=The Telegraph |last1=Bull |first1=JJ |date=21 May 2015 |accessdate=30 July 2019 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.espn.com/sports/soccer/news/_/id/5865935/barca-approach-blueprint-future |title=Barca past is link to the future |publisher=ESPN FC |last1=Cox |first1=Michael |date=30 November 2010 |accessdate=1 August 2019 }}</ref> His \"metronomic\" ability to control some matches has earned him the sobriquet, \"''The Puppet Master''\".<ref name=\"metronomic\"/><ref>{{cite web|url= http://www.football-news.org.uk/footballnews/101830/lionel-messi-wins-ballon-dor-for-second-time.html|title= Lionel Messi Wins Ballon D\u2019Or For Second Time|url-status= dead|archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20120112093528/http://www.football-news.org.uk/footballnews/101830/lionel-messi-wins-ballon-dor-for-second-time.html|archivedate= 12 January 2012|df= dmy-all}}</ref> Barcelona president [[Sandro Rosell]] believed that Xavi, together with Lionel Messi, Andr\u00e9s Iniesta and Sergio Busquets, perfected the club's ''[[tiki-taka]]'' style of play, a style introduced to the club by former coach [[Johan Cruyff]].<ref>{{cite news |url=https://int.soccerway.com/news/2014/January/10/rosell-unsure-over-tiki-taka-future/n256244/ |title=Rosell unsure over tiki-taka future |work=Soccerway |publisher=Global Sports Media |date=10 January 2013 |accessdate=22 May 2014 }}</ref> Xavi's creativity, range of passing, and unique set of skills have led many in the sport to regard him as one of the greatest passers and playmakers in history.<ref name=\"Most Skilled Passers in World Football History\"/><ref>{{cite web |url=https://bleacherreport.com/articles/1007318-world-football20-greatest-playmakers-in-the-history-of-football#slide0 |title=20 Greatest Playmakers in the History of World Football |publisher=Bleacher Report |last1=Sahu |first1=Amogha |date=2 January 2012 |accessdate=30 July 2019 }}</ref>\n\n==Media==\nXavi has a sponsorship deal with German sportswear and equipment supplier [[Adidas]] and has appeared in Adidas commercials alongside Lionel Messi, [[Luis Su\u00e1rez]] and [[Robin van Persie]].<ref>[http://news.adidas.com/GB/Latest-News/World-Cup-Adverts/s/9760c83b-60b8-4c83-b81f-443b8692da06 \"adidas launch long version 2014 FIFA World Cup Brazil\u2122 advert\"]. Adidas.com. Retrieved 4 March 2015</ref> Xavi features in EA Sports' [[FIFA (video game series)|''FIFA'' video game series]], and was the top passer in ''[[FIFA 15]]'' with a 91 rating.<ref>{{cite news |title=FIFA 16: 16 Best Passers On The Game |url=http://whatculture.com/gaming/fifa-16-16-best-passers-on-the-game |agency=WhatCulture.com. |date=11 June 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn November 2014, Xavi appeared in [[FIFA]]'s \"11 against [[Ebola virus disease|Ebola]]\" campaign with a selection of top football players from around the world, including Cristiano Ronaldo, [[Neymar]], [[Gareth Bale]] and [[Didier Drogba]].<ref name=\"Ebola\">[https://www.fifa.com/aboutfifa/footballdevelopment/medical/media/news/newsid=2475755/ \"Top players, FIFA, CAF and health experts unite against Ebola\"]. FIFA.com. Retrieved 4 March 2015</ref> Under the slogan \"Together, we can beat Ebola\", FIFA's campaign was done in conjunction with the [[Confederation of African Football]] (CAF) and health experts, with the players holding up 11 messages to raise awareness of the disease and ways to combat it.<ref name=\"Ebola\"/><ref>[http://www.fcbarcelona.com/football/first-team/detail/article/neymar-pique-and-xavi-in-fifa-campaign-against-ebola \"Neymar, Piqu\u00e9 and Xavi in FIFA campaign against Ebola\"]. FCBarcelona.com. Retrieved 4 March 2015</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nSince July 2013, Xavi has been married to Nuria Cunillera. Their daughter, Asia, was born on 3 January 2016.<ref>{{cite news |first=Javier |last=Miguel |title=Xavi Hern\u00e1ndez, padre de una ni\u00f1a llamada Asia |newspaper=Sport |date=3 January 2016 |url=http://www.sport.es/es/noticias/fuera-de-juego/xavi-hernandez-padre-una-nina-llamada-asia-4790849 |accessdate=3 January 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Career statistics==\n\n===Club===\n:Sources:<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.fcbarcelona.cat/web/english/futbol/temporada_10-11/estadistiques/jugadors/Xavi/fitxa.html |archive-url=https://archive.is/20120525235650/http://www.fcbarcelona.cat/web/english/futbol/temporada_10-11/estadistiques/jugadors/Xavi/fitxa.html |url-status=dead |archive-date=25 May 2012 |title=Official site statistics |publisher=FC Barcelona |accessdate=15 June 2010 }}</ref>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align: center\"\n|-\n!rowspan=\"2\"|Club\n!rowspan=\"2\"|Season\n!colspan=\"3\"|League\n!colspan=\"2\"|Cup<ref group=\"lower-alpha\">All appearances in [[Copa del Rey]] and [[Emir of Qatar Cup]]</ref>\n!colspan=\"2\"|Continental\n!colspan=\"2\"|Other\n!colspan=\"2\"|Total\n|-\n!Division||Apps||Goals||Apps||Goals||Apps||Goals||Apps||Goals||Apps||Goals\n|-\n|rowspan=\"4\"|[[FC Barcelona B|Barcelona B]]\n|[[1997\u201398 Segunda Divisi\u00f3n B|1997\u201398]]\n|[[Segunda Divisi\u00f3n B]]\n|33||2||colspan=\"2\"|\u2013||colspan=\"2\"|\u2013||6<ref group=\"lower-alpha\">All appearances in [[1998 Segunda Divisi\u00f3n B play-offs|Segunda Divisi\u00f3n B play-offs]]</ref>||0||39||2\n|-\n|[[1998\u201399 Segunda Divisi\u00f3n|1998\u201399]]\n|[[Segunda Divisi\u00f3n]]\n|18||0||colspan=\"2\"|\u2013||colspan=\"2\"|\u2013||colspan=\"2\"|\u2013||18||0\n|-\n|[[1999\u20132000 Segunda Divisi\u00f3n B|1999\u20132000]]\n|Segunda Divisi\u00f3n B\n|4||1||colspan=\"2\"|\u2013||colspan=\"2\"|\u2013||colspan=\"2\"|\u2013||4||1\n|-\n!colspan=\"2\"|Total\n!55!!3!!colspan=\"2\"|\u2013||colspan=\"2\"|\u2013||6||0||61!!3\n|-\n|rowspan=\"18\"|[[FC Barcelona|Barcelona]]\n|[[1998\u201399 La Liga|1998\u201399]]\n|rowspan=\"17\"|[[La Liga]]\n|17||1||2||0||6<ref group=\"lower-alpha\" name=\"UCL\">All appearances in [[UEFA Champions League]]</ref>||0||1<ref group=\"lower-alpha\" name=\"SDE\" >Appearances in [[Supercopa de Espa\u00f1a]]</ref>||1||26||2\n|-\n|[[1999\u20132000 FC Barcelona season|1999\u20132000]]\n|24||0||4||1||10<ref group=\"lower-alpha\" name=\"UCL\"/>||1||0||0||38||2\n|-\n|[[2000\u201301 FC Barcelona season|2000\u201301]]\n|20||2||7||0||9<ref group=\"lower-alpha\" >Five appearances in [[2000\u201301 UEFA Champions League|UEFA Champions League]], Four appearances in [[2000\u201301 UEFA Cup|UEFA Cup]]</ref>||0||colspan=\"2\"|\u2013||36||2\n|-\n|[[2001\u201302 FC Barcelona season|2001\u201302]]\n|35||4||1||0||16<ref group=\"lower-alpha\" name=\"UCL\"/>||0||colspan=\"2\"|\u2013||52||4\n|-\n|[[2002\u201303 FC Barcelona season|2002\u201303]]\n|29||2||1||0||14<ref group=\"lower-alpha\" name=\"UCL\"/>||1||colspan=\"2\"|\u2013||44||3\n|-\n|[[2003\u201304 FC Barcelona season|2003\u201304]]\n|36||4||6||0||7<ref group=\"lower-alpha\" name=\"UC\">All appearances in [[UEFA Cup]]</ref>||1||colspan=\"2\"|\u2013||49||5\n|-\n|[[2004\u201305 FC Barcelona season|2004\u201305]]\n|36||3||1||0||8<ref group=\"lower-alpha\" name=\"UCL\"/>||0||colspan=\"2\"|\u2013||45||3\n|-\n|[[2005\u201306 FC Barcelona season|2005\u201306]]\n|16||0||0||0||4<ref group=\"lower-alpha\" name=\"UCL\"/>||0||2<ref group=\"lower-alpha\" name=\"SDE\"/>||0||22||0\n|-\n|[[2006\u201307 FC Barcelona season|2006\u201307]]\n|35||3||7||2||7<ref group=\"lower-alpha\" name=\"UCL\"/>||0||5<ref group=\"lower-alpha\" >Two appearances and one goal in [[2006 Supercopa de Espa\u00f1a|Supercopa de Espa\u00f1a]], one appearance in [[2006 UEFA Super Cup|UEFA Super Cup]], two appearances in [[2006 FIFA Club World Cup|FIFA Club World Cup]]</ref>||1||54||6\n|-\n|[[2007\u201308 FC Barcelona season|2007\u201308]]\n|35||7||7||1||12<ref group=\"lower-alpha\" name=\"UCL\"/>||1||colspan=\"2\"|\u2013||54||9\n|-\n|[[2008\u201309 FC Barcelona season|2008\u201309]]\n|35||6||5||1||14<ref group=\"lower-alpha\" name=\"UCL\"/>|||3||colspan=\"2\"|\u2013||54||10\n|-<ref group=\"lower-alpha\" name=\"UCL\"/>\n|[[2009\u201310 FC Barcelona season|2009\u201310]]\n|34||3||3||2||11<ref group=\"lower-alpha\" name=\"UCL\"/>||1||5<ref group=\"lower-alpha\" >Two appearances and one goal in [[2009 Supercopa de Espa\u00f1a|Supercopa de Espa\u00f1a]], one appearance in [[2009 UEFA Super Cup|UEFA Super Cup]], two appearances in [[2009 FIFA Club World Cup|FIFA Club World Cup]]</ref>||1||53||7\n|-\n|[[2010\u20131