{"title_page": "Yucaipa Companies", "text_new": "{{Infobox company \n|  name   = The Yucaipa Companies\n|  logo   = [[Image:Yucaipa Companies logo.png|250px|Yucaipa Companies logo]]\n|  type   = [[Private Company|Private]]\n|  foundation     = {{start date and age|1986}}\n|  founder        = [[Ronald Burkle]]\n|  location       = [[Los Angeles]], [[California]], [[United States]]\n|  industry       = [[Private equity]]\n|  products       = [[Leveraged buyout]]\n|  assets         = \n|  homepage       = [http://yucaipaco.com yucaipaco.com]\n|  num_employees  = \n}}\n\n'''The Yucaipa Companies LLC''' is an American private equity firm founded in 1986 by [[Ronald Burkle]].<ref name=history>{{cite web|title=Yucaipa Cos. History|url=http://www.fundinguniverse.com/company-histories/yucaipa-cos-history/|website=Funding Universe|accessdate=6 February 2015}}</ref> It specializes in [[private equity]] and [[venture capital]], with a focus on [[Middle-market company|middle-market companies]], [[growth capital]], [[Consolidation (business)|industry consolidation]], [[leveraged buyouts]], and turnaround investments. It generally invests $25\u2013$300 million in companies with $300\u2013$500 million in revenues.<ref name=bb>{{cite web|title=Company Overview of The Yucaipa Companies, LLC|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/research/stocks/private/snapshot.asp?privcapId=23465|website=Bloomberg Business|accessdate=6 February 2015}}</ref>\n\nYucaipa has a history of leveraged buyouts in [[supermarket]] and [[grocery]] chains, beginning with Jurgensen's Markets in 1986. After several standalone investments in the late 1980s, it went on to lead the [[Consolidation (business)|consolidation]] of West Coast retail that occurred during the 1990s due in part to the rise of discount centers like [[Wal-Mart]].<ref>{{cite journal|author1=Phil R. Kaufman|title=Structural Change in the U.S. Food Industry|journal=FoodReview|date=May\u2013August 2000|volume=23|issue=2|pages=29\u201334|url=http://www2.econ.iastate.edu/classes/econ135/lawrence/Grocery%20Mergers.pdf}}</ref><ref name=kit/> In October 2014, The Yucaipa Companies acquired British retailer [[Tesco]]'s [[Fresh & Easy]] chain five years after it had entered the U.S. market.\n\nIts investments include [[Relativity Media|Relativity]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.crunchbase.com/organization/relativity-media-pl|title=Relativity Media|website=Crunchbase|language=en|access-date=2019-04-30}}</ref>\n\n== History ==\n[[File:Yucaipa Companies Boeing 757-200 Lebeda.jpg|thumb|300px|Yucaipa [[Boeing 757-200]] [[bizjet]]]]\n* 1987: [[Food 4 Less]] grocery [[Franchising|franchise]] of [[Kansas City Metropolitan Area|Kansas City]] [[Takeover|acquired]] for $35 million\n* 1989: [[Boys Markets]] acquired for $375 million\n* 1991: [[Alpha Beta]] [[California]] supermarket chain acquired for $271 million\n* 1994: [[Smitty's (retailer)|Smitty's]] [[Phoenix, Arizona|Phoenix]]-based supermarket operator acquired for $138 million\n* 1994: [[Ralphs Grocery Co.]] [[Southern California]] supermarket chain acquired for $1.5 billion; Alpha Beta and Boys outlets subsequently [[rebranded]] as Ralphs<ref name=kit>{{cite news|last1=Roane|first1=Kit R.|title=California Grocery Deal: Yucaipa to Buy Ralphs| url= https://www.nytimes.com/1994/09/15/business/company-news-california-grocery-deal-yucaipa-to-buy-ralphs.html | work = New York Times|date=September 15, 1994}}</ref>\n<!---  \"The resulting business, to be called the Ralphs Grocery Company, would have 431 stores under the Ralphs or Food 4 Less brands; outlets of lesser-known chains like Viva, Boys, and Alpha Beta would become either Ralphs or Food 4 Less stores. Business savings would come from standardized store formats and less duplicated services.\" --->\n** 1997: [[Ralphs]]/[[Food 4 Less]] [[Mergers and acquisitions|merged]] with [[Fred Meyer]]\n*** 1998: [[Fred Meyer]] sold to [[Kroger]] for $8 billion\n* 1995: [[Dominick's]], a [[Chicago]]-based grocery store chain, acquired for $750 million\n** 1998: Dominick's sold for $1.85 billion to [[Safeway Inc.|Safeway]]\n* 1999: invests $3 million in [[GameSpy]], and $25 million in [[Cyrk (Company)|Cyrk, Inc.]]\n* 2004:\tTDS Logistics purchased by Yucaipa (according to TDS Logistics site [http://www.tdslogistics.com/en/content/view/4/3/])\n* 2004: Yucaipa along with Piccadily Restaurant Investment Group, LLC a special purpose entity formed by Ramy El-Batrawi acquires [[Piccadilly Restaurants]]\n* 2005: Yucaipa becomes the majority shareholder in [[Aloha Airlines]] in a $100 million bid to purchase the airline.\n* 2005: acquires 40% stake in [[Pathmark]] for $150 million<ref>{{cite news|url=http://articles.latimes.com/2005/jun/10/business/fi-burkle10 |title=Pathmark-Yucaipa Deal OKd |work= Los Angeles Times |date=June 10, 2005 |accessdate=2013-09-11}}</ref>\n**2007: acquires stake in [[The Great Atlantic & Pacific Tea Company]] as part of GA&P's acquisition of Pathmark<ref>{{cite news|last=Canada |first=Hillary |url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB10000872396390444301704577631794110130890 |title=Yucaipa Returns to Market With $1.65 Billion Target |work =Wall Street Journal |date=September 4, 2012 |accessdate=2013-09-11}}</ref>\n* 2008: acquires stake in [[Barnes & Noble]]<ref name=\"wsj\">{{cite news|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB10001424052702303918204577448972458172412 |title=Burkle's Yucaipa Divests B&N Stake  |work =Wall Street Journal |date=June 5, 2012 |accessdate=2013-09-11}}</ref>\n** 2009: Yucaipa doubles its stake in Barnes & Noble to 16.8% during [[e-reader]] war with [[Amazon.com]], citing [[corporate governance]] concerns<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/2009/11/13/barnesnoble-burkle-idUSN1348217720091113 |title= Burkle ups Barnes & Noble stake, cites concerns |publisher=Reuters |date=2009-11-13 |accessdate=2013-09-11 |first=Alexandria |last=Sage}}</ref> \n*** 2012: divests Barnes & Noble shares to Yucaipa investors<ref name=\"wsj\" />\n* 2011: increases stake in [[The Great Atlantic & Pacific Tea Company]] as part of a restructuring following its bankruptcy<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.thedeal.com/content/restructuring/ap-wins-approval-of-exit-financing-files-plan.php |title=A&P wins exit financing, files plan  |work =The Deal Pipeline |date= |accessdate=2013-09-11}}</ref>\n* 2012: Stake in [[Barneys New York]]<ref>[http://www.sfgate.com/cgi-bin/article.cgi?f=/g/a/2012/05/08/bloomberg_articlesM3NVYH6VDKJ001-M3POB.DTL ] {{webarchive|url=https://archive.is/20120910054605/http://www.sfgate.com/cgi-bin/article.cgi?f=/g/a/2012/05/08/bloomberg_articlesM3NVYH6VDKJ001-M3POB.DTL |date=2012-09-10 }}</ref>\n* 2014: Acquired [[Fresh & Easy]] from [[Tesco]]<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/business-24040346 |title=Tesco offloads loss making Fresh & Easy chain |publisher=bbc.co.uk |date=2013-09-10 |accessdate=2013-09-10}}</ref>\n\n=== Aloha Airlines purchase ===\nIn February 2006, [[Aloha Airlines]] was taken into private ownership by Yucaipa Companies and Aloha Investment Group, LLC head by Ramy El-Batrawi. After 61 years in business, passenger operations shut down on March 31, 2008, due to rising fuel prices, new competition for inter-island travel, a [[Credit crunch|tightening credit]] market, and dwindling interest by investors in the airline industry.\n\nIn January 2011 Yucaipa won federal Bankruptcy Court approval to buy the Aloha name and other intellectual property for $1.5 million with a stipulation that it not resell the name to Mesa Air Group, the parent of [[go! Mokulele]].{{Citation needed|date=August 2012}} It is unknown at this time what the future plans are for the Aloha name.\n\n<!--- section heading linked to from another article; please try not to edit ---> \nCaught in the [[pink slime]] controversy and with interim chief executive Ron Allen citing \"ongoing media attention\" that has \"dramatically reduced the demand for all ground beef products\" in 2012, Yucaipa's AFA declared [[Chapter 11]] bankruptcy. Based in [[King of Prussia, Pennsylvania|King of Prussia]], [[Pennsylvania]], AFA at the time the controversy broke had about 850 employees and annual revenues of $958 million.<ref>Milford, Phil, and Shruti Date Singh, [http://www.sfgate.com/cgi-bin/article.cgi?f=/g/a/2012/04/02/bloomberg_articlesM1UMUE6JTSE801-M1UYN.DTL \"AFA Foods Files for Bankruptcy Citing 'Pink Slime' Coverage\"], April 2, 2012, ''[[Bloomberg L.P.|Bloomberg News]]''. Retrieved 2012-04-02.</ref><ref>[[Al Lewis (columnist)|Lewis, Al]], [http://www.marketwatch.com/story/dude-people-just-dont-want-to-eat-pink-slime-2012-04-04?link=home_carousel \u201cDude, people just don\u2019t want to eat pink slime\u201d], ''[[MarketWatch]]'', April 4, 2012. Retrieved 2012-04-04.</ref>\n\n==Controversy==\nFormer U.S. President [[Bill Clinton]], a close friend of founder Ron Burkle, was an advisor to Yucaipa.<ref>{{cite news| title= Bill Clinton Leaves Yucaipa Business Partnerships|  url= https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB123716092427335513 | author= [[John R. Emshwiller]] | date= March 16, 2009 |work= Wall Street Journal}}</ref> From 2003 to 2006, Bill and Hillary Clintons' [[Tax return (United States)|tax returns]] show total Yucaipa partnership income of $12.5 million. According to the 2007 summary provided by [[Hillary Clinton]]'s [[Hillary Clinton presidential campaign, 2008|presidential campaign]], the Clintons earned $2.75 million from the Yucaipa partnership.<ref name=mike>{{cite news|last1=McIntire|first1=Mike|title=Clintons Made $109 Million in Last 8 Years| url= https://www.nytimes.com/2008/04/05/us/politics/05clintons.html?pagewanted=all |work=New York Times|date=April 5, 2008}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Private equity and venture capital}}\n[[Category:1986 establishments in California]]\n[[Category:Aloha Airlines]]\n[[Category:Barnes & Noble]]\n[[Category:American companies established in 1986]]\n[[Category:Financial services companies established in 1986]]\n[[Category:Companies based in Los Angeles]]\n[[Category:GameSpy]]\n[[Category:Holding companies of the United States]]\n[[Category:Private equity firms of the United States]]\n[[Category:The Great Atlantic & Pacific Tea Company]]\n[[Category:Venture capital firms of the United States]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox company \n|  name   = The Yucaipa Companies\n|  logo   = [[Image:Yucaipa Companies logo.png|250px|Yucaipa Companies logo]]\n|  type   = [[Private Company|Private]]\n|  foundation     = {{start date and age|1986}}\n|  founder        = [[Ronald Burkle]]\n|  location       = [[Los Angeles]], [[California]], [[United States]]\n|  industry       = [[Private equity]]\n|  products       = [[Leveraged buyout]]\n|  assets         = \n|  homepage       = [http://yucaipaco.com yucaipaco.com]\n|  num_employees  = \n}}\n\n'''The Yucaipa Companies, LLC''' is an American private equity firm founded in 1986 by [[Ronald Burkle]].<ref name=history>{{cite web|title=Yucaipa Cos. History|url=http://www.fundinguniverse.com/company-histories/yucaipa-cos-history/|website=Funding Universe|accessdate=6 February 2015}}</ref> It specializes in [[private equity]] and [[venture capital]], with a focus on [[Middle-market company|middle-market companies]], [[growth capital]], [[Consolidation (business)|industry consolidation]], [[leveraged buyouts]], and turnaround investments. It generally invests $25\u2013$300 million in companies with $300\u2013$500 million in revenues.<ref name=bb>{{cite web|title=Company Overview of The Yucaipa Companies, LLC|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/research/stocks/private/snapshot.asp?privcapId=23465|website=Bloomberg Business|accessdate=6 February 2015}}</ref>\n\nYucaipa has a history of leveraged buyouts in [[supermarket]] and [[grocery]] chains, beginning with Jurgensen's Markets in 1986. After several standalone investments in the late 1980s, it went on to lead the [[Consolidation (business)|consolidation]] of West Coast retail that occurred during the 1990s due in part to the rise of discount centers like [[Wal-Mart]].<ref>{{cite journal|author1=Phil R. Kaufman|title=Structural Change in the U.S. Food Industry|journal=FoodReview|date=May\u2013August 2000|volume=23|issue=2|pages=29\u201334|url=http://www2.econ.iastate.edu/classes/econ135/lawrence/Grocery%20Mergers.pdf}}</ref><ref name=kit/> In October 2014, The Yucaipa Companies acquired British retailer [[Tesco]]'s [[Fresh & Easy]] chain five years after it had entered the U.S. market.\n\nIts investments include [[Relativity Media|Relativity]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.crunchbase.com/organization/relativity-media-pl|title=Relativity Media|website=Crunchbase|language=en|access-date=2019-04-30}}</ref>\n\n== History ==\n[[File:Yucaipa Companies Boeing 757-200 Lebeda.jpg|thumb|300px|Yucaipa [[Boeing 757-200]] [[bizjet]]]]\n* 1987: [[Food 4 Less]] grocery [[Franchising|franchise]] of [[Kansas City Metropolitan Area|Kansas City]] [[Takeover|acquired]] for $35 million\n* 1989: [[Boys Markets]] acquired for $375 million\n* 1991: [[Alpha Beta]] [[California]] supermarket chain acquired for $271 million\n* 1994: [[Smitty's (retailer)|Smitty's]] [[Phoenix, Arizona|Phoenix]]-based supermarket operator acquired for $138 million\n* 1994: [[Ralphs Grocery Co.]] [[Southern California]] supermarket chain acquired for $1.5 billion; Alpha Beta and Boys outlets subsequently [[rebranded]] as Ralphs<ref name=kit>{{cite news|last1=Roane|first1=Kit R.|title=California Grocery Deal: Yucaipa to Buy Ralphs| url= https://www.nytimes.com/1994/09/15/business/company-news-california-grocery-deal-yucaipa-to-buy-ralphs.html | work = New York Times|date=September 15, 1994}}</ref>\n<!---  \"The resulting business, to be called the Ralphs Grocery Company, would have 431 stores under the Ralphs or Food 4 Less brands; outlets of lesser-known chains like Viva, Boys, and Alpha Beta would become either Ralphs or Food 4 Less stores. Business savings would come from standardized store formats and less duplicated services.\" --->\n** 1997: [[Ralphs]]/[[Food 4 Less]] [[Mergers and acquisitions|merged]] with [[Fred Meyer]]\n*** 1998: [[Fred Meyer]] sold to [[Kroger]] for $8 billion\n* 1995: [[Dominick's]], a [[Chicago]]-based grocery store chain, acquired for $750 million\n** 1998: Dominick's sold for $1.85 billion to [[Safeway Inc.|Safeway]]\n* 1999: invests $3 million in [[GameSpy]], and $25 million in [[Cyrk (Company)|Cyrk, Inc.]]\n* 2004:\tTDS Logistics purchased by Yucaipa (according to TDS Logistics site [http://www.tdslogistics.com/en/content/view/4/3/])\n* 2004: Yucaipa along with Piccadily Restaurant Investment Group, LLC a special purpose entity formed by Ramy El-Batrawi acquires [[Piccadilly Restaurants]]\n* 2005: Yucaipa becomes the majority shareholder in [[Aloha Airlines]] in a $100 million bid to purchase the airline.\n* 2005: acquires 40% stake in [[Pathmark]] for $150 million<ref>{{cite news|url=http://articles.latimes.com/2005/jun/10/business/fi-burkle10 |title=Pathmark-Yucaipa Deal OKd |work= Los Angeles Times |date=June 10, 2005 |accessdate=2013-09-11}}</ref>\n**2007: acquires stake in [[The Great Atlantic & Pacific Tea Company]] as part of GA&P's acquisition of Pathmark<ref>{{cite news|last=Canada |first=Hillary |url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB10000872396390444301704577631794110130890 |title=Yucaipa Returns to Market With $1.65 Billion Target |work =Wall Street Journal |date=September 4, 2012 |accessdate=2013-09-11}}</ref>\n* 2008: acquires stake in [[Barnes & Noble]]<ref name=\"wsj\">{{cite news|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB10001424052702303918204577448972458172412 |title=Burkle's Yucaipa Divests B&N Stake  |work =Wall Street Journal |date=June 5, 2012 |accessdate=2013-09-11}}</ref>\n** 2009: Yucaipa doubles its stake in Barnes & Noble to 16.8% during [[e-reader]] war with [[Amazon.com]], citing [[corporate governance]] concerns<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/2009/11/13/barnesnoble-burkle-idUSN1348217720091113 |title= Burkle ups Barnes & Noble stake, cites concerns |publisher=Reuters |date=2009-11-13 |accessdate=2013-09-11 |first=Alexandria |last=Sage}}</ref> \n*** 2012: divests Barnes & Noble shares to Yucaipa investors<ref name=\"wsj\" />\n* 2011: increases stake in [[The Great Atlantic & Pacific Tea Company]] as part of a restructuring following its bankruptcy<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.thedeal.com/content/restructuring/ap-wins-approval-of-exit-financing-files-plan.php |title=A&P wins exit financing, files plan  |work =The Deal Pipeline |date= |accessdate=2013-09-11}}</ref>\n* 2012: Stake in [[Barneys New York]]<ref>[http://www.sfgate.com/cgi-bin/article.cgi?f=/g/a/2012/05/08/bloomberg_articlesM3NVYH6VDKJ001-M3POB.DTL ] {{webarchive|url=https://archive.is/20120910054605/http://www.sfgate.com/cgi-bin/article.cgi?f=/g/a/2012/05/08/bloomberg_articlesM3NVYH6VDKJ001-M3POB.DTL |date=2012-09-10 }}</ref>\n* 2014: Acquired [[Fresh & Easy]] from [[Tesco]]<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/business-24040346 |title=Tesco offloads loss making Fresh & Easy chain |publisher=bbc.co.uk |date=2013-09-10 |accessdate=2013-09-10}}</ref>\n\n=== Aloha Airlines purchase ===\nIn February 2006, [[Aloha Airlines]] was taken into private ownership by Yucaipa Companies and Aloha Investment Group, LLC head by Ramy El-Batrawi. After 61 years in business, passenger operations shut down on March 31, 2008, due to rising fuel prices, new competition for inter-island travel, a [[Credit crunch|tightening credit]] market, and dwindling interest by investors in the airline industry.\n\nIn January 2011 Yucaipa won federal Bankruptcy Court approval to buy the Aloha name and other intellectual property for $1.5 million with a stipulation that it not resell the name to Mesa Air Group, the parent of [[go! Mokulele]].{{Citation needed|date=August 2012}} It is unknown at this time what the future plans are for the Aloha name.\n\n<!--- section heading linked to from another article; please try not to edit ---> \nCaught in the [[pink slime]] controversy and with interim chief executive Ron Allen citing \"ongoing media attention\" that has \"dramatically reduced the demand for all ground beef products\" in 2012, Yucaipa's AFA declared [[Chapter 11]] bankruptcy. Based in [[King of Prussia, Pennsylvania|King of Prussia]], [[Pennsylvania]], AFA at the time the controversy broke had about 850 employees and annual revenues of $958 million.<ref>Milford, Phil, and Shruti Date Singh, [http://www.sfgate.com/cgi-bin/article.cgi?f=/g/a/2012/04/02/bloomberg_articlesM1UMUE6JTSE801-M1UYN.DTL \"AFA Foods Files for Bankruptcy Citing 'Pink Slime' Coverage\"], April 2, 2012, ''[[Bloomberg L.P.|Bloomberg News]]''. Retrieved 2012-04-02.</ref><ref>[[Al Lewis (columnist)|Lewis, Al]], [http://www.marketwatch.com/story/dude-people-just-dont-want-to-eat-pink-slime-2012-04-04?link=home_carousel \u201cDude, people just don\u2019t want to eat pink slime\u201d], ''[[MarketWatch]]'', April 4, 2012. Retrieved 2012-04-04.</ref>\n\n==Controversy==\nFormer U.S. President [[Bill Clinton]], a close friend of founder Ron Burkle, was an advisor to Yucaipa.<ref>{{cite news| title= Bill Clinton Leaves Yucaipa Business Partnerships|  url= https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB123716092427335513 | author= [[John R. Emshwiller]] | date= March 16, 2009 |work= Wall Street Journal}}</ref> From 2003 to 2006, Bill and Hillary Clintons' [[Tax return (United States)|tax returns]] show total Yucaipa partnership income of $12.5 million. According to the 2007 summary provided by [[Hillary Clinton]]'s [[Hillary Clinton presidential campaign, 2008|presidential campaign]], the Clintons earned $2.75 million from the Yucaipa partnership.<ref name=mike>{{cite news|last1=McIntire|first1=Mike|title=Clintons Made $109 Million in Last 8 Years| url= https://www.nytimes.com/2008/04/05/us/politics/05clintons.html?pagewanted=all |work=New York Times|date=April 5, 2008}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Private equity and venture capital}}\n[[Cate